"I think it's very interesting today these things codified and we need to have Congress's role here, and that's what we're waiting for right now. We had the Genius Act that's sort of in the books. We don't want to reopen that, by the way. I know some people would like to, but then there's the Clarity Act. Tell us how important these two pieces of legislation are and what they do for Ripple and the overall industry.""So, the Clarity Act, I was on a show a little over a month ago, and I predicted that we'd see the Clarity Act signed by the end of April. I'm going to say that the likelihood of that has gone down, but I'll say by the end of May, so give me an extra 30 days there. Everyone's still at the table. We're still making progress. Ultimately, there's going to have to be a compromise on this key issue around how rewards are managed. Ripple doesn't actually personally have a dog in that fight, but we think to get the Clarity Act for the industry, for the US to be competitive, for these entrepreneurs not to move offshore, for crypto capital and investment not to move offshore, we need the Clarity Act to get done. I am very optimistic. I was at a dinner two days ago in Washington, D.C., and sat next to people who are much smarter than I am about how law gets made. I'll say, watching the sausage getting made here has not been pretty, but they gave me more optimism that we are going to get there. And the point that one gentleman said to me, he's like, 'Look, when people are at their most frustrated is when you finally get it done because people will compromise.'Yeah. And from this White House, we're seeing amazing leadership to push this forward. So, I think we're going to get there. It's just taking a little longer than we thought.""So, what happens to Ripple once clarity gets passed?""Well, it won't change Ripple's business too much. What it does is it unlocks the banks in the United States who have been a little bit fearful about, 'Should I lean into this industry? What if there is a future Gary Gensler, and then how am I going to have to unwind things?'So if we get that codified into law, it's an unlock for the banks around the world, particularly in the United States. We have seen banks say to us, 'Look, we understand that you won the lawsuit and you have clarity that XRP is not a security.'And last week, obviously, that's another great step forward. But if we get it codified into law, I think you'll see more of the largest financial institutions in the United States and really the world lean in more to this industry.""Tell me more about XRP and what the main use cases are so that our audience understands how it impacts them.""So XRP, much like Bitcoin, is an open-source digital asset. There's a blockchain called the XRP Ledger. Ripple is one of the primary participants in that ecosystem. We

00:25:36.630 --> 00:25:36.640
really use it primarily around payments. There are some other things we're doing around settlement for the prime brokerage business. But we're seeing entrepreneurs, because XRP is so fast in terms of transactions, so low cost, and also energy efficient, you're seeing more and more developers and entrepreneurs build on top of the XRP Ledger. And that's around things like the tokenization of real-world assets. We're working with Guggenheim on a money market tokenization. The Land Authority of Dubai is doing land registry on the XRP Ledger. There are lots of examples, and it's really about how do we take block-efficient, highly scalable, very fast, and low-cost blockchain technologies to enable these settlement technologies that I think are going to continue to rewire financial infrastructure around the globe.""And the acquisitions that you made sort of complement one another in that regard because you've got treasury, but that's going to complement what happens in the brokerage for sure.""I've been very happy about how those acquisitions have gone, and I think people see how we're stitching these pieces together. Some in crypto, I think, have done acquisitions that are intra-crypto, inside the echo chamber. We've only done things kind of outside the echo chamber because we think it's really about how do we build those bridges between traditional finance and what we call decentralized finance or crypto. Both GTreasury and Hidden Road are just tremendous examples of that, and we're seeing their clients want to lean in. So we're seeing great adoption, and I'm excited. I mean, 2026 is going to be a record year for us for sure.""Congratulations on that. That's incredible. When you think about what's going on with traditional financial services, little by little they're leaning in. It took them a while, but how do you think the competitive landscape changes now that you see the big guys understanding what has been taking place under their noses, but they didn't want to get involved?""Yeah, it's been interesting to see, and I'm sure you've seen those. Your guests, the people you've interviewed. We went from 'it's rat poison'to 'that's a pet rock.'You remember some of these quotes; I think they were on your show. Now, some of those same leaders are coming around and saying, 'Oh, okay. I see how these technologies work.'And look, I'll give Larry Fink at BlackRock credit. He was one of the first really senior, well-respected leaders to step forward and say, 'No, I do see real value and real technology value to how these technologies can be applied.'So we are seeing a shift from the JPMorgan's. We're seeing people start to be more exploratory: 'Oh, okay. How could we use stablecoins?'It's really also driven by customers. As I said earlier, the CEOs and boards of directors of companies across the United States are asking their finance organizations, 'Are we using stablecoins?'"Are they more efficient? Because remember, the other unlock around stablecoins is now you can access them and use them 24/7. They don't close at 4:00 on a Friday afternoon; you can settle a real estate transaction on Saturday. Did you hear that?

